<subSubSection pageId="41" pageNumber="42" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="41.[151,1436,782,1602]" pageId="41" pageNumber="42">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,315,1507,1531]" inLineHeading="true" pageId="41" pageNumber="42" reason="1">Remarks.</emphasis>
This species can easily be recognized by the two cross veins between the claval veins of the forewings and by the structure of the male genitalia. It resembles 
<taxonomicName box="[842,1000,1542,1566]" class="Insecta" family="Cicadellidae" genus="Durgades" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="41" pageNumber="42" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="dunchensis">
<emphasis box="[842,1000,1542,1566]" italics="true" pageId="41" pageNumber="42">D. dunchensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, but differs in the structure of the pygofer and aedeagus.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
